<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-Curl-Divergence">
    <title>5.4 Curl and Divergence</title>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            In this section, we will introduce two important concepts in vector calculus: curl and divergence. 
            These concepts are used to describe the behavior of vector fields in three-dimensional space.
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <definition xml:id="def-curl-3d">
  <title>The Curl of a Vector Field</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>\mathbf{F} = P\mathbf{i} + Q\mathbf{j} + R\mathbf{k}</m> is a vector field on <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> and the partial derivatives of <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, and <m>R</m> all exist, then the <term>curl</term> of <m>\mathbf{F}</m> is the vector field defined by:
      <me>\operatorname{curl} \mathbf{F} = \left(\frac{\partial R}{\partial y} - \frac{\partial Q}{\partial z}\right) \mathbf{i} + \left(\frac{\partial P}{\partial z} - \frac{\partial R}{\partial x}\right) \mathbf{j} + \left(\frac{\partial Q}{\partial x} - \frac{\partial P}{\partial y}\right) \mathbf{k}.</me>
      In terms of the del gradient operator, this can be written as a formal cross product:
      <me>\operatorname{curl} \mathbf{F} = \nabla \times \mathbf{F}.</me>
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>

<example xml:id="ex-curl-calculation">
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>\mathbf{F}(x,y,z) = xz\mathbf{i} + xyz\mathbf{j} - y^2\mathbf{k}</m>, find <m>\operatorname{curl}\mathbf{F}</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <strong>Step 1: Set Up the Formal Cross Product Matrix</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      We express the curl as a symbolic 3-by-3 determinant using the component fields <m>P = xz</m>, <m>Q = xyz</m>, and <m>R = -y^2</m>:
      <me>\operatorname{curl} \mathbf{F} = \nabla \times \mathbf{F} = \begin{vmatrix} \mathbf{i} \amp \mathbf{j} \amp \mathbf{k} \\ \frac{\partial}{\partial x} \amp \frac{\partial}{\partial y} \amp \frac{\partial}{\partial z} \\ xz \amp xyz \amp -y^2 \end{vmatrix}</me>
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Step 2: Expand the Determinant by Coactors</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      Expanding along the first row yields three 2-by-2 component derivative blocks:
      <md>
        <mrow>\operatorname{curl} \mathbf{F} \amp = \begin{vmatrix} \frac{\partial}{\partial y} \amp \frac{\partial}{\partial z} \\ xyz \amp -y^2 \end{vmatrix}\mathbf{i} - \begin{vmatrix} \frac{\partial}{\partial x} \amp \frac{\partial}{\partial z} \\ xz \amp -y^2 \end{vmatrix}\mathbf{j} + \begin{vmatrix} \frac{\partial}{\partial x} \amp \frac{\partial}{\partial y} \\ xz \amp xyz \end{vmatrix}\mathbf{k}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \left( \frac{\partial}{\partial y}(-y^2) - \frac{\partial}{\partial z}(xyz) \right)\mathbf{i} - \left( \frac{\partial}{\partial x}(-y^2) - \frac{\partial}{\partial z}(xz) \right)\mathbf{j} + \left( \frac{\partial}{\partial x}(xyz) - \frac{\partial}{\partial y}(xz) \right)\mathbf{k}</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Step 3: Evaluate Partial Derivatives and Simplify</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      Computing each bracketed operation yields:
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            For the <m>\mathbf{i}</m> component:
            <me>\frac{\partial}{\partial y}(-y^2) - \frac{\partial}{\partial z}(xyz) = -2y - xy.</me>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            For the <m>\mathbf{j}</m> component (including the outer subtraction sign):
            <me>-\left( \frac{\partial}{\partial x}(-y^2) - \frac{\partial}{\partial z}(xz) \right) = -\left( 0 - x \right) = x.</me>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            For the <m>\mathbf{k}</m> component:
            <me>\frac{\partial}{\partial x}(xyz) - \frac{\partial}{\partial y}(xz) = yz - 0 = yz.</me>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Step 4: Conclusion</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      Combining the evaluated terms gives the final vector field:
      <me>\operatorname{curl} \mathbf{F} = (-2y - xy)\mathbf{i} + x\mathbf{j} + yz\mathbf{k} = \langle -2y - xy, \ x, \ yz \rangle.</me>
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

<theorem xml:id="thm-curl-conservative-test">
  <title>The Curl of a Gradient Field</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>f</m> is a function of three variables that has continuous second-order partial derivatives, then:
      <me>\operatorname{curl}(\nabla f) = \mathbf{0}.</me>
      Since a conservative vector field is defined as one for which there exists a potential scalar function such that <m>\mathbf{F}=\nabla f</m>, it follows that if <m>\mathbf{F}</m> is a conservative vector field, then:
      <me>\operatorname{curl} \mathbf{F} = \mathbf{0}.</me>
    </p>
  </statement>
</theorem>

<example xml:id="ex-show-not-conservative-3d">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Show that the vector field <m>\mathbf{F}(x,y,z) = xz\mathbf{i} + xyz\mathbf{j} - y^2\mathbf{k}</m> is not conservative.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <strong>Step 1: Compute the Curl of the Field</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      According to <xref ref="thm-curl-conservative-test" />, if a vector field is conservative, its curl must equal the zero vector. Let's calculate <m>\operatorname{curl} \mathbf{F}</m> using a symbolic cross product:
      <me>\operatorname{curl} \mathbf{F} = \nabla \times \mathbf{F} = \begin{vmatrix} \mathbf{i} \amp \mathbf{j} \amp \mathbf{k} \\ \frac{\partial}{\partial x} \amp \frac{\partial}{\partial y} \amp \frac{\partial}{\partial z} \\ xz \amp xyz \amp -y^2 \end{vmatrix}</me>
      Expanding along the first row yields:
      <md>
        <mrow>\operatorname{curl} \mathbf{F} \amp = \left( \frac{\partial}{\partial y}(-y^2) - \frac{\partial}{\partial z}(xyz) \right)\mathbf{i} - \left( \frac{\partial}{\partial x}(-y^2) - \frac{\partial}{\partial z}(xz) \right)\mathbf{j} + \left( \frac{\partial}{\partial x}(xyz) - \frac{\partial}{\partial y}(xz) \right)\mathbf{k}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = (-2y - xy)\mathbf{i} - (0 - x)\mathbf{j} + (yz - 0)\mathbf{k}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \langle -2y - xy, \ x, \ yz \rangle.</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Step 2: Conclusion</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      Because <m>\operatorname{curl} \mathbf{F} = \langle -2y - xy, \ x, \ yz \rangle \neq \langle 0, 0, 0 \rangle</m> throughout <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>, the field fails the zero-curl condition. Therefore, <m>\mathbf{F}</m> is <strong>not conservative</strong>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-show-conservative-3d">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Show that the vector field <m>\mathbf{F}(x,y,z) = y^2z^3\mathbf{i} + 2xyz^3\mathbf{j} + 3xy^2z^2\mathbf{k}</m> is conservative.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <strong>Step 1: Compute the Curl of the Field</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      We match the given parameters to the component fields <m>P = y^2z^3</m>, <m>Q = 2xyz^3</m>, and <m>R = 3xy^2z^2</m>. We evaluate their symbolic determinant:
      <me>\operatorname{curl} \mathbf{F} = \nabla \times \mathbf{F} = \begin{vmatrix} \mathbf{i} \amp \mathbf{j} \amp \mathbf{k} \\ \frac{\partial}{\partial x} \amp \frac{\partial}{\partial y} \amp \frac{\partial}{\partial z} \\ y^2z^3 \amp 2xyz^3 \amp 3xy^2z^2 \end{vmatrix}</me>
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Step 2: Evaluate Component Derivatives</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      Expanding by row minors and taking partial derivatives:
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            For the <m>\mathbf{i}</m> component:
            <me>\frac{\partial R}{\partial y} - \frac{\partial Q}{\partial z} = \frac{\partial}{\partial y}(3xy^2z^2) - \frac{\partial}{\partial z}(2xyz^3) = 6xyz^2 - 6xyz^2 = 0.</me>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            For the <m>\mathbf{j}</m> component:
            <me>-\left( \frac{\partial R}{\partial x} - \frac{\partial P}{\partial z} \right) = -\left( \frac{\partial}{\partial x}(3xy^2z^2) - \frac{\partial}{\partial z}(y^2z^3) \right) = -\left( 3y^2z^2 - 3y^2z^2 \right) = 0.</me>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            For the <m>\mathbf{k}</m> component:
            <me>\frac{\partial Q}{\partial x} - \frac{\partial P}{\partial y} = \frac{\partial}{\partial x}(2xyz^3) - \frac{\partial}{\partial y}(y^2z^3) = 2yz^3 - 2yz^3 = 0.</me>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Step 3: Conclusion</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      Combining our calculated vector paths yields:
      <me>\operatorname{curl} \mathbf{F} = 0\mathbf{i} + 0\mathbf{j} + 0\mathbf{k} = \langle 0, 0, 0 \rangle = \mathbf{0}.</me>
      Because <m>\operatorname{curl} \mathbf{F} = \mathbf{0}</m> continuously everywhere on the simply-connected domain <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>, the test is satisfied. Therefore, the vector field <m>\mathbf{F}</m> is <strong>conservative</strong>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

<definition xml:id="def-divergence-3d">
  <title>The Divergence of a Vector Field</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>\mathbf{F} = P\mathbf{i} + Q\mathbf{j} + R\mathbf{k}</m> is a vector field on <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> and the partial derivatives <m>\frac{\partial P}{\partial x}</m>, <m>\frac{\partial Q}{\partial y}</m>, and <m>\frac{\partial R}{\partial z}</m> all exist, then the <term>divergence</term> of <m>\mathbf{F}</m> is the scalar field defined by:
      <me>\operatorname{div} \mathbf{F} = \frac{\partial P}{\partial x} + \frac{\partial Q}{\partial y} + \frac{\partial R}{\partial z}.</me>
      In terms of the del gradient operator, this can be written as a formal dot product:
      <me>\operatorname{div} \mathbf{F} = \nabla \cdot \mathbf{F}.</me>
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>

<example xml:id="ex-divergence-evaluation">
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>\mathbf{F}(x,y,z) = xz\mathbf{i} + xyz\mathbf{j} - y^2\mathbf{k}</m>, find <m>\operatorname{div}\mathbf{F}</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <strong>Step 1: Identify Component Functions</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      We match the given vector field to the standard component form <m>\mathbf{F} = P\mathbf{i} + Q\mathbf{j} + R\mathbf{k}</m>:
      <me>P(x,y,z) = xz, \quad Q(x,y,z) = xyz, \quad R(x,y,z) = -y^2.</me>
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Step 2: Compute Partial Derivatives</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      We find the corresponding first-order partial derivative for each independent component:
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            Differentiate <m>P</m> with respect to <m>x</m>:
            <me>\frac{\partial P}{\partial x} = \frac{\partial}{\partial x}(xz) = z.</me>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Differentiate <m>Q</m> with respect to <m>y</m>:
            <me>\frac{\partial Q}{\partial y} = \frac{\partial}{\partial y}(xyz) = xz.</me>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Differentiate <m>R</m> with respect to <m>z</m>:
            <me>\frac{\partial R}{\partial z} = \frac{\partial}{\partial z}(-y^2) = 0.</me>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Step 3: Combine and Simplify</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      According to the divergence definition, we sum the three partial derivative terms together:
      <md>
        <mrow>\operatorname{div} \mathbf{F} \amp = \frac{\partial P}{\partial x} + \frac{\partial Q}{\partial y} + \frac{\partial R}{\partial z}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = z + xz + 0 = z + xz.</mrow>
      </md>
      The divergence of the vector field is the scalar function <m>z + xz</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

<theorem xml:id="thm-div-curl-zero">
  <title>The Divergence of a Curl</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>\mathbf{F} = P\mathbf{i} + Q\mathbf{j} + R\mathbf{k}</m> is a vector field on <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> and its component functions <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, and <m>R</m> have continuous second-order partial derivatives, then:
      <me>\operatorname{div}(\operatorname{curl} \mathbf{F}) = \nabla \cdot (\nabla \times \mathbf{F}) = 0.</me>
    </p>
  </statement>
</theorem>

<example xml:id="ex-show-not-a-curl">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Show that the vector field <m>\mathbf{F}(x,y,z) = xz\mathbf{i} + xyz\mathbf{j} - y^2\mathbf{k}</m> cannot be written as the curl of another vector field; that is, <m>\mathbf{F} \neq \operatorname{curl} \mathbf{G}</m> for any vector field <m>\mathbf{G}</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <strong>Step 1: Apply the Divergence of a Curl Theorem</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      According to <xref ref="thm-div-curl-zero" />, if a vector field <m>\mathbf{F}</m> can be expressed as the curl of some vector field <m>\mathbf{G}</m> (meaning <m>\mathbf{F} = \operatorname{curl} \mathbf{G}</m>), then taking its divergence must automatically yield zero:
      <me>\operatorname{div} \mathbf{F} = \operatorname{div}(\operatorname{curl} \mathbf{G}) = 0.</me>
      Therefore, to show that <m>\mathbf{F}</m> cannot be written as a curl, we only need to compute <m>\operatorname{div} \mathbf{F}</m> and verify that it is not identically zero.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Step 2: Calculate the Divergence of <m>\mathbf{F}</m></strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      We extract the component fields from the problem statement: <m>P = xz</m>, <m>Q = xyz</m>, and <m>R = -y^2</m>. We apply the standard divergence sum formula:
      <md>
        <mrow>\operatorname{div} \mathbf{F} \amp = \frac{\partial P}{\partial x} + \frac{\partial Q}{\partial y} + \frac{\partial R}{\partial z}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{\partial}{\partial x}(xz) + \frac{\partial}{\partial y}(xyz) + \frac{\partial}{\partial z}(-y^2)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = z + xz + 0 = z(1 + x).</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Step 3: Conclusion</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      The result shows that <m>\operatorname{div} \mathbf{F} = z(1+x)</m>, which is not identically zero everywhere in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> (for instance, at the point <m>(1,1,1)</m>, <m>\operatorname{div}\mathbf{F} = 2</m>).
    </p>
    <p>
      Because <m>\operatorname{div} \mathbf{F} \neq 0</m>, it fails the fundamental identity requirement of a curl field. Therefore, <m>\mathbf{F}</m> <strong>cannot</strong> be written as the curl of another vector field (<m>\mathbf{F} \neq \operatorname{curl} \mathbf{G}</m>).
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>





</section>